  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical concept—it's something I've seen play out in my own life and the lives of my family members. Growing up with parents who both had upper secondary education, I was always encouraged to pursue learning, but the reality of STEM fields often feels alien to someone without a college degree. I've noticed how people with lower educational backgrounds, especially those from marginalized communities, can feel the weight of stereotypes when they're in environments dominated by those who've had more formal training. For example, when my nephew, who's really smart but only has a high school diploma, tried to explain a car engine to me, he was nervous because he felt like he wasn't 'qualified' enough. That's stereotype threat in action—being afraid of confirming a negative stereotype about your group. It's not just about confidence; it's about the psychological burden of being perceived as less capable. I think we absolutely should address it, but the approach has to be practical and community-centered. Instead of top-down solutions that might feel alienating, we need to create spaces where people feel safe to learn without fear of judgment. In my shop, I've seen this happen with younger mechanics who feel intimidated by the technical jargon. They need more hands-on training and mentorship that validates their skills. The key is to shift the narrative from 'you need a degree to be good at this' to 'you can learn this through experience and practice.' As a mechanic who's spent years fixing cars without a college degree, I know that real skills matter more than credentials. Addressing stereotype threat means recognizing that everyone has a right to learn and grow, regardless of their background.",
